  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The historian appends a few notices here concerning David's wives: \"And David had taken Ahinoam from Jezreel; thus they also both became his wives.\" The expression \"also\" points to David's marriage with Michal, the daughter of Saul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 18:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Jezreel is not the city of that name in the tribe of Issachar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but the one in the mountains of Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:56",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
